Cancer is the second leading cause of mortality in humans, globally. There are an estimated 18.1 million new cases each year and it accounted for 9.6 million deaths in 2018 (

). The treatment of cancer typically involves the removal of cancerous or tumor cells by surgery and radiation therapy, both of which are usually followed by chemotherapy (

). However, obstacles such as side effects of the cancer drugs, e.g. cardiotoxicity, pulmonary dysfunction, lymphedema, etc. (

; 

; 

) and the reoccurrence of cancerous cells, make this disease extremely difficult to completely eradicate, ultimately leading to the loss of life. A number of studies have demonstrated that chronic inflammation may cause several 
types
of cancer (

; 

; 

). The discovery of the link between inflammation and cancer has led to research into drugs that can target inflammatory mediators and cancerous cell growth. Therefore, we have explored natural products from fungi that have anti-inflammatory and anti-proliferative activities from fungi for chemoprevention and chemotherapy drug candidates.

Fungi is one of the most significant sources for the discovery of potential drug candidates with research into their metabolites and compounds having produced a large number of well documented reports (

; 

; 

). The 

Biscogniauxia

genus previously belonged to the wood-decaying fungi, the 
Xylariaceae
family. It was resurrected to the Graphostomataceae family in 2017, which comprises five genera that are made up of more than 136 species (

). Unlike Xylarials, for which there has been numerous reports on their bioactive compounds (

), there has only been a small number from this genus e.g. sesquiterpenoid analogues from 
Graphostoma
sp. that were found to have potent anti-inflammatory properties (

, 

).

Compound 1 was obtained as a yellow viscous oil and the molecular formula C 15 H 22 O 2 was assigned by the positive ion peak in HRESIMS at m/z 257.1519 [M+Na] + (calc. for C 15 H 22 O 2 Na, 257.1517). The 1 H NMR data ( Table 1 ) displayed proton signals of one olefinic methine at δ H 5.11 (t, J = 6.8, H-10), three methines at δ H 3.16 (s, H-4), 2.50 (br t, J = 5.9, H-6) and 2.39 (t, J = 5.9, H-2), three methylenes at δ H 2.06 (d, J = 10.5, H-1a) and 2.24 (dt, J = 10.5, 5.9, H-1b), 1.97 (m, H-9), and 1.76 (dd, J = 10.3, 6.9, H-8), and four methyls at δ H 1.68 (s, H-12), 1.60 (s, H-13), 1.49 (s, H-15) and 1.00 (s, H-14). The 13 C NMR data ( Table 2 ) showed a carbonyl ketone signal at δ C 206.1 (C-5) that corresponded with the strong absorption band of a carbonyl ketone at 1711 cm 1 in
the IR spectrum, and two olefinic signals at δ C 132.1 (C-11) and 123.7 (C-10). The COSY correlations of H-1 to H-2 and H- 6 in association with the key HMBC correlations of H-1 to C-2, C-3, C-5, C-6 and C-7, CH 3 -14 to C-2, C-6, C-7 and C-8, and CH 3 -15 to C-2, C-3 and C-4 suggested the presence of a bicyclo [3.1.1]heptane ring ( Fig. 2 ), a core structure of the bergamotene-type sesquiterpenoid (
;
;
). This was supported by the multiplicity patterns of the bridge-ring protons, i.e. H-1, H-2 and H-6 ( Fig. 3 ). The two bridgehead methine protons H-2 and H-6 that appeared as a triplet revealed the 3 J H2-H1b , 3 J H6-H1b and 4 J H2-H6 correlations with coupling constants of 5.9 Hz (
), which contributed to the doublet of triplet of H-1b ( 3 J H1b-H2 = 5.9 Hz, 3 J H1b-H6 = 5.9 Hz and 2 J H1b-H1a = 10.5 Hz). However, the H-1a appeared as a doublet due to its coupling only with H-1b ( 2 J H1a-H1b = 10.5 Hz). A possible explanation for this could be that the dihedral angle of H-1a to the adjacent protons H-2 and H-6 ( 3 J ≈ 0 Hz) is around 90 ◦ thus there is no coupling among them. Signals from two high-field oxygenated carbons appeared at δ C 59.8 (C-3) and 59.2 (C-4) and the HMBC correlation of CH 3 -15 to C-2, C-3 and C-4 that corresponds with the absence of an OH-stretching absorption band in the IR spectrum. This revealed a 3,4-epoxide ring which is different from the typical bergamotene-core structure. The 4-methylpent-3-en-1-yl moiety was deduced by the COSY correlation of H-9 to H-8 and H-10 and the HMBC correlations of CH 3 -12,13 to C-10 and C-11, H-8,9 to C-7 and CH 3 -14 to C-7 and C-8 that supported the connection at C-7 of the bicyclic ring. The key NOESY correlations ( Fig. 4 ) of H-1b to H-8, and CH 3 -14 to H-4 indicated an exo -face pentenyl-substituted chain on the tricyclic ring, suggesting the relative configuration of 2 R *, 3 R *, 4 R *, 6 S * and 7 S *. The comparison of experimental and calculated ECD spectra ( Fig. 5 ), showing Cotton effects at 208 (Δ ε = +0.03), 216 (Δ ε = 0.03), 228 (Δ ε = +0.01) and 324 (Δ ε = +0.03) nm that were similar to the calculated spectrum for (2 R ,3 R ,4 R ,6 S ,7 S )-1, led to the assignment of the absolute configuration of 1. The structure of 1 was therefore depicted as shown in Fig. 1 and named as xylariterpenoid L (
).

The 1 H and 13 C NMR spectra of 2–5 showed some degree of similarity to 1. Compound 2 was obtained as yellow viscous oil and the molecular formula C 15 H 24 O 4 was determined according to the positive ion peak in HRESIMS at m/z 291.1573 [M+Na] + (calc. for C 15 H 24 O 4 Na, 291.1572). The shifted proton signal at δ H 3.33 (br d, J = 10.0, H-10), which corresponded to the carbon signals at δ C 78.7 (C-10) and 73.2 (C-11), indicated the presence of a dihydroxy group instead of a double bond as in 1. This was supported by the absorption band of an OH-stretching at 3403 cm 1 in
the IR spectrum. The 13 C NMR data of 2 showed some splitting carbon signals such as at C-2, C-5, C-6, C-7 and C-14, which suggested the mixture of two diastereomers (2a and 2b). The diastereomeric ratio of 2a and 2b could not be assigned based on the overlapping of almost every 1 H NMR signal. Nevertheless, the ratio of 1:0.7 of 2a and 2b was estimated from the integration of splitting 13 C NMR signals (
). The key NOESY correlation of H-4 to CH 3 -14, 15 confirmed the exo -face of the pentenyl group. The comparison of the ECD spectra with 1 ( Fig. 5 ) suggested a similar absolute configuration on the tricyclic ring as 2 R , 3 R , 4 R , 6 S and 7 S . However, because they were isolated as a mixture, the configuration of C-10 could not be determined in this work. On the basis of the above data, 2 was identified as 10, 11-dihydroxy xylariterpenoid L, named as xylariterpenoid M.

Compound 3 was isolated as a colorless viscous oil. Its molecular formula was C 15 H 22 O, based on the positive ion peak at m/z 219.1743 [M+H] + (calc. for C 15 H 23 O, 219.1749) in HRESIMS. When compared to 1, the 1 H NMR data of 3 showed an additional olefinic proton signal at δ H 5.73 (s, H-4). This corresponded to the 13 C NMR signals at 170.0 (C-3) and 121.5 (C-4). The HMBC correlation of CH 3 -15 to C-2, C-3 and C-4 ( Fig. 2 ) suggested that there was a double bond on the bicyclo [3.1.1] heptane ring instead of an epoxide ring. The key NOESY correlations of H-1b to H-8 and CH 3 -14 to H-4 ( Fig. 4 ) suggested a pentenyl chain in the exo -face of the bridge ring and the experimental ECD spectrum of 3 showed a similar pattern to the calculated ECD spectrum of (2 S ,6 S ,7 S )-3 ( Fig. 6 ). According to the above data, 3 was an undescribed bergamotene, named as xylariterpenoid N. Compounds 4 and 5 were isolated as a mixture in this work. The NMR spectroscopic data suggested partially similar structures to that of 2 and 3. For example, the signals of an alkenyl group on the bicyclo [3.1.1]heptane ring and a 10,11-dihydroxy group on the pentenyl chain. An intensive comparison of the NMR and ECD data to those in literature revealed that they are known xylariterpenoids A (4) and B (5) (
;
).

Compound 6 was a yellow viscous oil. The IR spectrum displayed the strong absorption band of an OH stretching at 3344 cm 1 and the weak absorption band of a C––C stretching at 1707 cm 1 . At first glance, the 1 H NMR data of 6 resembled 1 and 3, showing two olefinic signals at δ H 5.71 (m, H-4) and 5.14 (t, J = 6.6, H-10) and four methyl signals at δ H 1.82 (s, H-15), 1.69 (s, H-12), 1.62 (s, H-13) and 1.22 (s, H-14). The 13 C NMR data also displayed four olefinic signals at δ C 132.1 (C-11), 131.2 (C-3), 126.0 (C-4) and 123.9 (C-10). Two oxygenated methine signals at δ H 4.29 (br s, H-1) and 3.81 (s, H-2) corresponded to 13 C NMR signals at δ C 72.2 (C-2) and 70.8 (C-1). The COSY correlation of H-9 to H-8 and H-10 in association with the HMBC correlations of CH 3 -12,13 to C-10 and C-11, and CH 3 -14 to C-6, C-7 and C-8 indicated a 2-hydroxy-6- methylhept-5-en-2-yl chain. The COSY correlations from H-1 to H-6 and the key HMBC correlations of CH 3 -15 to C-2, C-3 and C-4, H-1 to C-2, C-3, C-5, C-6 and C-7, H-2 to C-1, C-3, C-4, C-6 and C-15, H-4 to C-2, C-6 and C-15, and H-5 to C-3, C-4 and C-6 confirmed the 3-methylcyclohex-3-ene moiety. This data revealed that 6 was a bisabolol derivative with a substituted 1,2-dihydroxy group. Bisabolol is a precursor that goes through a C2–C7 ring closure to form the bergamotene (
). The key NOESY correlation of H-1 to H-2 and H-6 ( Fig. 4 ), and the broad singlets of H-1 and H-2 ( 3 J H1-H2 ≈ 3 J H1-H6 ≈ 0 Hz), corresponding to the cis form of the dihydroxy group (
), led to the assignment of the relative configuration of 6 as 1 S *, 2 R * and 6 S *. This was supported by a comparison of the multiplicity patterns of H-1 (br s), H-2 (s) and H-6 (m) with four known synthetic compounds with similar core structures (
;
). It resembled (1 S ,2 R ,6 R )- 3-methyl-6-(prop-1-en-2-yl)cyclohex-3-ene-1, 2-diol (see Fig. S 46 in SI). The absolute configuration was indicated by comparing experimental and calculated ECD spectra ( Fig. 7 ). The spectrum showed Cotton effects at 210 (Δ ε = +0.35) and 223 (Δ ε = +0.15) nm, which were similar to the calculated spectrum of (1 R ,2 S ,6 R , 7 S )-6. Based on the above data and the positive ion peak at m/z 277.1784 [M+Na] + in HRESIMS accounting for the molecular formula C 15 H 22 O (calc. for C 15 H 26 O 3 Na, 277.1784), compound 6 was determined as (1 R ,2 S ,6 R )-6-(( S )-2-hydroxy-6-methylhept-5-en-2-yl)-3-met hylcyclohex-3-ene-1,2-diol, named (1 R ,2 S ,6 R ,7 S )-1,2-dihydroxy- α -bisa bolol.

Compound 7 was identified as α -pyrone derivative, named as 6- [(1 R )-1-hydroxy-1-methyl-2-propenyl]-4-methoxy-3-methyl-2 H -pyran-2-one. The molecular formula C 11 H 14 O 4 was deduced from the HRESIMS ion peak at m/z 233.0791 [M+Na] + (calc. for C 11 H 14 O 4 Na, 233.0790). The IR spectrum showed the broad absorption band of an OH stretching at 3393 cm 1 and the strong absorption band of an α,β- unsaturated carbonyl group of the α -pyrone ring at 1677 cm 1 (
). The 4-methoxy-3-methyl-2 H -pyran-2-one-6-yl ring was deduced from the 1 H NMR signals of olefinic at δ H 6.46 (s, H-5), methoxy at δ H 3.91 (s, H-12) and methyl at δ H 1.63 (s, H-7), together with the 13 C NMR signals of carbonyl lactone at δ C 165.9 (C-2) and olefinic carbons at δ C 166.0 (C-4), 165.1 (C-6), 101.6 (C-3) and 91.7 (C-5). This was supported by HMBC correlations of CH 3 -7 to C-2, C-3 and C-4, H-5 to C-4 and C-6, and CH 3 O-12 to C-4. The 1 H NMR data also exhibited a set of olefinic proton signals at δ H 6.15 (dd, J = 17.3, 10.7, H-9), 5.40 (d, J = 17.3, H-10) and 5.24 (d, J = 10.7, H-10), corresponding to 13 C NMR signals at δ C 140.5 (C-9) and 114.7 (C-10). An oxygenated carbon was observed at δ C 73.7 (C-8). The COSY correlation of H-9 to H-10 and the HMBC correlations of H-10 to C-8 and C-9, and H-11 to C-6, C-8 and C-9 revealed the presence of a 2-hydroxybut-3-en-2-yl chain, substituted at C-6 of the α -pyrone ring. When compared to compounds from literature, 7 closely resembled synthesized 6-[(1 S )-1-hydroxy-1-methyl-2-propenyl]-4-meth oxy-3,5-dimethyl-2 H -pyran-2-one, except for the lack of a methyl group at C-5 (
). The 8 R was assigned based on the [α] D 24.7 -99.0 ( c 0.60, CHCl 3 ), in contrast to the reported S configuration ([α] D +120.0, c 1.01 CHCl 3 ). The α -pyrone derivatives 8–12 were recognized immediately from their NMR spectra and the data were compared to those in literature. The results showed that they were the known phomopyrone A (8) (
), gulypyrone B (9) (
), 6-(1 ′ ,2 ′ -dimethyloxiran-1 ′ -yl)-4-methoxy-3-methyl-2 H -pyr an-2-one (10) (
), nectriapyrone (11) (
) and vermopyrone (12) (
).

